  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "At the end of this business they made their report to the king. \"All the vessels which King Ahaz had thrown away, i.e., made worthy of rejection,\" are the copper altar of burnt-offering, the brazen sea, and the lavers upon the bases (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 16:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 16:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). הכנּוּ, we have prepared, is a shorter form of הכיונוּ; cf. Gesen. Gramm. 72. 5, and J. Olshausen, hebr. Grammat. S. 565. The altar of Jahve is the altar of burnt-offering; cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 29:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
